@NODE "Parse" "Parse Command"
@TOC "HintsTips"
@NEXT "HintsTips"
@PREV "HintsTips"

@{par}                               @{fg shine}"Parse" Command@{fg text}
@{par}
@{par}This function can be used when you want to run a program for which you have not
set up a button, but which requires arguments. It can also be used for running
a program on the selected file(s) (ie. basically for when you are too lazy to
open a shell window!).
@{par}
@{par}For example, if you select a file called @{b}Widget.Nad@{ub} and use Parse, you will be
asked for a string to go before and after it. This will be built into a
command-line which is then executed. Let's say that @{b}Widget.Nad@{ub} was a picture
you wanted to show with @{b}ViewTek@{ub}, and you wanted to use ViewTek's @{b}NoBusy@{ub} option,
you would enter @{b}Viewtek@{ub} in the first requester and @{b}NoBusy@{ub} in the second one.
@{b}Note@{ub} that you are not limited to single word answers - this is just an
example:
@{par}
@{par}@{fg fill}Viewtek Widget.Nad NoBusy@{fg text}
@{par}
@{par}...would then be executed, and the picture displayed.
@{par}
@{par}As another example, say that you have downloaded a new program called @{b}NadBuster@{ub}
which requires a shell-argument @{b}Config@{ub} to tell it where its config file is. Let
us also say you have created and saved this config as @{b}RAM:NadBuster.config@{ub}. All
you have to do is select the @{b}NadBuster@{ub} program file, click on Parse, leave the
first requester blank (just hit RETURN), and type @{b}Config RAM:NadBuster.config@{ub}.
@{par}
@{par}@{fg fill}NadBuster RAM:NadBuster.config@{fg text} would then be run.
@{par}
@{par}OK, I hope you get the idea now. Want to know how many lines the actual
function which took so long to describe is?...  Just one @{fg shine}@{b}:@{fg text}@{ub}-).
@{par}(It is not complicated - just very usefull!).
@{par}
@{par} TYPE:      COMMAND:
@{par} @{b}------------------------------------------------------------------------------@{ub}@{fg fill}
@{par} @{b}AmigaDOS@{ub} - {RsEnter String To Preceed Filename} {o} {RsEnter String To @{b}@{fg shine}->@{ub}@{fg fill}
@{par}            Follow Filename}@{fg text}
@{par} @{b}------------------------------------------------------------------------------@{ub}
@{par}
@{par}Check the following flags:
@{par}
@{par} @{fg fill}· CD source
@{par} · Do all files
@{par} · No file quote  (** Optional, sometimes you'll want this off **)
@{par} · Output to window
@{par} · Window close button@{fg text}
@{par}
@{par}@{b}NOTE:@{ub} the @{fg shine}@{b}->@{fg text}@{ub} means @{b}continued on the next line@{ub}; however, you would @{b}type this
@{par}      all on one line@{ub}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "FileType" "FileType"
@TOC "HintsTips"
@NEXT "HintsTips"
@PREV "HintsTips"

@{par}                             @{fg shine}FileType Priorities@{fg text}
@{par}
@{par}Special thanks to @{"Jonathan Potter" LINK "Thanks"} for helping me out with some of the details
used in this section.
@{par}
@{par}Usually, you will want all of your filetypes to have a priority of zero.
However, the filetype priorities become very useful when you have one filetype
which is a subset of another. For example, 24-bit IFF-pictures are a subset of
regular IFF-pictures, and while only a 24-bit picture will match the first
type, ANY type of IFF-picture will match the second.
@{par}
@{par}I've got about 8 different picture viewers on my harddrive. On my setup, PPShow
seems to be the best one for showing 24-bit IFF-pictures, but for other things
I prefer to use Viewtek. Obviously I've set the 24-bit IFF-picture filetype to
use PPShow, and the IFF-picture datatype to use Viewtek, but this isn't enough.
DOpus will act on the first filetype which matches the file, so you have to do
something to ensure that a 24-bit IFF-picture isn't matched by the IFF-picture
filetype! This is simple to do - just put the 24-bit filetype at a higher
priority. My IFF-picture filetype is at priority 0 (zero), so I set the 24-bit
filetype to 1 (one), and everything works fine.
@{par}
@{par}Similarily, I have a filetype which matches ASCII text and extracts binary data
from the file in one of two ways: UUEncoded data via drag-n-drop and User2
(which is "Unpack" on my setup). Because a UUEncoded file would match the
standard ASCII filetype, I set the UUEncoded filetype to a higher priority.
@{par}@{u}                                                                               @{uu}
@{par}
@{par}                             @{b}Undocumented Feature@{ub}
@{par}
@{par}DOpus5 has some internal filetypes which exist even if you were to delete ALL
the @{b}DOpus5:Filetypes/@{ub} files.
@{par}
@{par}Essentially there are two sets of filetypes: those set at priority -125, which
display pictures, play sounds, etc., and the "last-resort" filetype at priority
-127, which just calls @{b}SmartRead@{ub} if a file was @{b}Double-Clicked@{ub}, and @{b}Copy@{ub} if it
was @{b}Drag-n-Drop@{ub}ped.
@{par}
@{par}@{b}NOTE@{ub}: The "last-restort" will only get used if NO filetype matches are found
@{par}      (ie. if none of the -125 filetypes are matched).
@{par}
@{par}The filetype priority -126 is left unused so that you may create a filetype
which will match ALL files (MatchName #?) and define an action (ie. for Double-
Click, User1, Drag-n-Drop, etc) you wish preformed if absolutely none of the
other filetypes match the slected file.
@{par}
@{par}@{b}NOTE@{ub}: In order to have an action preformed by the filetype priorities greater
@{par}      than -126 (ie -125 and up), you must have actions defined for them.
@{par}
@{par}Since the priority -127 filetype actions for Double-Click and Drag-n-Drop are
what most people would want as the "last-resort," your -126 filetype probably
won't define anything for those actions. However, the -127 filetype has nothing
defined for the @{b}UserX@{ub} actions. This means that if you do @{b}User1@{ub} on a file and
none of the filetypes match the file (AND you have a User1 action defined),
absolutely nothing will happen. So to MAKE something happen by @{i}default@{ui} on the
@{b}UserX@{ub} actions, you may define them in your -126 filetype.
@{par}
@{par}@{b}FINAL NOTE@{ub}: You DO NOT have to define every action for each filetype. For
@{par}            example, my @{i}default@{ui} filetype has the Drag-n-Drop action defined as
@{par}            the internal @{b}Copy@{ub} command. If you are editing a filetype, say for
@{par}            IFF-pictures, and you want them to be copied when Drag-n-Drop, you
@{par}            can leave the Drag-n-Drop action blank because the pictures will
@{par}            drop through the IFF-picture filetype and be caught by your @{i}default @{ui}
@{par}            filetype (assuming they don't match another filetype on the way, of
@{par}            course!).
@{par}@{u}                                                                               @{uu}
@{par}
@{par}I know this stuff sounds complicated (try explaining it @{fg shine}@{b}:@{ub}@{fg text}), but if you require
help/clarification then feel free to contact @{"one of us" LINK "Author"}.

@ENDNODE
